^B@2^*Bcaitlin: ^*N|cp||at|Caitlin: So, for those who were not here last let us repeat the important points. What does Reading the Opponents' Cards mean to you at this point?|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT|
-- It is about you as declarer reading opponents' cards.So, how do we get clues? |
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|
-- We get them by:
^c@2^Z@3A. From the bidding. For example When an opponent opens and his partner does not have enough HCP(high card points) to respond.|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|
B) When an opponent overcalls. For example, when one opponent makes a takeout double but partner can't respond as your side has the HCP. |
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


AT|
C. From the lead. For example a lead of Ace (leading Ace/King) typically promises King unless doubleton. Or the lead of King typically promises Queen. Another one is Partner opened 1S but opponents are in 4H and you lead @S10. What does that tell the partner? Sure, most likely a singleton particularly if he has the @S9 or it is in the dummy. If you have not supported, the modern theory is to low from 3. Another good example is if opponent has preempted 3H and leads say a Diamond. That lead most likely ids a singleton.|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


AT| 
D) When one opponent preempts and you and partner 'buy' the contract. A preemptive bid allows you to put 6 cards if it is a 2-level preempt; 7 cards if 3-level preempt.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


AT|

-- So, this is 2nd of 4 sessions on reading HCPs and we shall see that you only have to count ONE opponents' hand. Then we spend 4 sessions on Reading Opponents Cards by shape of one opponent's hand. Okay, let's get down to business.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


