AT|   wyoming33: Count points and distributions.|
PG| ***** 77 ***** |


AT|
--Counting seems beyond so many of you as I often hear from you folks! Is it that hard to count ONE of opponent's hands? Always slow down and REVIEW BIDDING or LACK OF, ANALYZE the LEAD, COUNT ONE OPPONENT'S HAND, and COUNT your trumps. In this board we did not count our @H suit BUT we counted East's @HA and @HJ. |
PG| ***** 78 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bcaitlin: ^*N|cp||at|With each of the hands we have looked at thus far, our play West for to hold  @SKx (Board 4), or East with trump @HKx (Board 5) has worked and these have been the only ways to make the contract.  On a bad day West will have the @SKxx and East the Kxx, but then there would be no way to make the contract and everyone else playing such hands will go down. And on Board 6, we counted and saw it was unlikely that East has the @DQ as that makes for a 1NT opener. Sure, East could have had 2 doubletons and thus not opened 1NT but playing West for the @DQ makes sense. |
PG| ***** 79 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bcaitlin: ^*N|cp||at|Always give yourself the best chance and by counting one opponent’s cards, we will know all four hands. It won’t come to you overnight, but slow down and review the bidding or lack of and analyze the lead! I have commentated on BBO for many World Class events and these experts don’t play to the first trick quickly. Indeed it is rare that they play quickly. Remember it is OK to type in ‘thinking’ and if your opponents rush you, find new opponents to play against!
|
